WEBVTT

00:01.001 --> 00:04.004
♪ E... ♪

00:04.004 --> 00:07.007
♪ 'verybody... ♪

00:09.133 --> 00:11.011
♪ Needs a friend ♪

00:11.011 --> 00:12.596
JULES:
Never feel more alone than when

00:12.596 --> 00:15.933
I'm putting a fitted sheet on a bed
as one human person.

00:15.933 --> 00:17.559
This is a team activity.

00:20.687 --> 00:22.731
‐ You know, we do have

00:22.731 --> 00:24.483
a fourth friend who could've been helpful

00:24.483 --> 00:26.401
in this situation.

00:26.401 --> 00:28.612
‐ As a child of many divorces,

00:28.612 --> 00:30.656
I really can't handle
when you and Madison fight.

00:30.656 --> 00:33.951
‐ Oh my god, are we gonna have
to have separate Friendsgivings?

00:33.951 --> 00:37.162
‐ Madison is going with Ruby to Australia

00:37.162 --> 00:40.165
and not to Greece with me! We're just...

00:40.165 --> 00:41.875
giving each other some space.

00:42.709 --> 00:46.004
Two continents of space.

00:46.004 --> 00:48.423
♪ Need me ♪

00:48.423 --> 00:50.300
It's not like she's tried
reaching out to me.

00:50.300 --> 00:53.303
She can text me any time she wants.
‐ I'm sure she will.

00:53.303 --> 00:55.514
[phone buzzing]

00:55.514 --> 00:58.892
Some days, I have to convince myself
that I am not at least part witch.

01:00.310 --> 01:01.812
[buzzing stops]

01:03.981 --> 01:06.775
‐ Well?!
‐ It's Fender.

01:06.775 --> 01:09.486
‐ Okay, and why are you not more excited?

01:09.486 --> 01:12.614
‐ Because he's on tour with who
knows how many groupies probably.

01:12.614 --> 01:14.199
I'm not exactly trying to get my hopes up.

01:14.199 --> 01:15.659
[phone ringing]

01:15.659 --> 01:17.286
‐ Is it one of the groupies?

01:17.286 --> 01:18.912
‐ Uh, basically.

01:18.912 --> 01:21.498
It's my mom. This is
the third time she's called me.

01:21.498 --> 01:24.960
I love her, but I just cannot
do Sharon Wiley right now.

01:24.960 --> 01:28.672
‐ Okay, are we the only two people in your
life you are talking to right now, or...

01:28.672 --> 01:31.383
‐ Pretty much pleading
the fifth emotionally, yeah.

01:31.383 --> 01:33.552
‐ If my mom called me
three times in a row,

01:33.552 --> 01:36.680
I would be fully convinced that someone
in my family had passed away.

01:36.680 --> 01:37.973
How are you not freaking out?

01:37.973 --> 01:39.850
‐ Well, I wasn't before.

01:39.850 --> 01:42.311
‐ I mean, three times is kind of a lot.

01:42.311 --> 01:44.354
‐ Shit.
[applause]

01:44.354 --> 01:46.940
[laughter]

01:46.940 --> 01:49.193
‐ Alright, improv fans!

01:49.193 --> 01:52.404
For our first scene, our prompt is
"reasons Jules' mom

01:52.404 --> 01:55.991
has called her three times."
Now, to kick us off,

01:55.991 --> 01:57.826
could we get a suggestion
from the audience?

01:57.826 --> 02:01.079
‐ Oh! Um, her dad died?
‐ Oh, nice one.

02:01.079 --> 02:02.331
‐ Dead dad. Perfect.

02:02.331 --> 02:05.334
‐ What?! No, no, no!
ACTOR: [chewing] Um, hey, honey?

02:05.334 --> 02:08.795
You didn't put peanuts in this, did you?
‐ Yes, and I sure did,

02:08.795 --> 02:11.632
because it's pad Thai,
and I love Asian cuisine!

02:11.632 --> 02:13.509
ACTOR 1:
Yes, and I know you do,

02:13.509 --> 02:16.720
but I'm allergic! Oh!
‐ [gasps] Oh no!

02:16.720 --> 02:19.181
[gagging]
ACTOR 2: Freeze!

02:19.181 --> 02:20.724
[audience laughter]

02:22.559 --> 02:24.061
Oh my chest!

02:24.061 --> 02:27.314
I'm having a massively
unexpected heart attack!

02:27.314 --> 02:30.651
‐ Yes, and it's not a heart attack!
It's a stroke! It's a stroke.

02:30.651 --> 02:32.778
‐ Jason, she's doing that thing again
where she says "yes and,"

02:32.778 --> 02:34.696
but then disagrees with me.
‐ Stay in the scene, Rich.

02:34.696 --> 02:36.281
‐ It throws me off.

02:36.281 --> 02:37.866
‐ Okay, Kelly, get in there. Tag in.

02:40.244 --> 02:43.080
‐ Bang! I just murdered my own husband,

02:43.080 --> 02:46.208
Jules' father, in cold blood.

02:46.208 --> 02:48.585
‐ Oh wow.
‐ What?

02:48.585 --> 02:50.629
‐ Yes, and I'm dead!

02:50.629 --> 02:53.674
I'm dead, and it's Jules' fault
for not picking up

02:53.674 --> 02:54.842
the phone in time!

02:54.842 --> 02:56.343
[curtains rattling]

02:57.261 --> 02:59.263
‐ I should probably call my mom.

03:00.264 --> 03:03.267
♪ theme song ♪

03:06.854 --> 03:09.857
[sighs] Please don't let
anyone actually be dead.

03:09.857 --> 03:13.193
SHARON [on voicemail]:
Hi, Julesy! Don't worry, it's just me.

03:13.193 --> 03:15.362
We finally found a buyer for the house,

03:15.362 --> 03:17.447
so Dad and I need you
to come home this weekend

03:17.447 --> 03:19.241
to help pack up your old bedroom.

03:19.241 --> 03:21.952
JULES' DAD [on voicemail]:
Honey? A‐are you talking to me?

03:21.952 --> 03:24.663
SHARON:
No, Craig, I'm talking to Jules!

03:24.663 --> 03:26.665
CRAIG: You're what?!
SHARON: I'm talking to‐‐

03:26.665 --> 03:29.167
Anyway, love you. Bye.
[laughs]

03:31.670 --> 03:35.215
MADISON: I think option C
is better for brand recognition.

03:35.215 --> 03:37.217
More memorable.
STELLA: Okay, cool.

03:37.217 --> 03:38.802
That's what we were thinking, too.

03:38.802 --> 03:40.220
♪ music playing ♪

03:40.220 --> 03:42.222
Jules did these designs, by the way.

03:42.222 --> 03:44.266
‐ Mm, she did a good job.
‐ Yeah.

03:44.266 --> 03:46.602
Izzy and I saw her today.

03:46.602 --> 03:49.229
‐ [sighs] You're being real
subtle bringing this up, Stel.

03:49.229 --> 03:51.440
‐ Why don't you just text her?
MADISON: Because!

03:51.440 --> 03:53.066
I know she thinks Ruby is shady,

03:53.066 --> 03:55.694
and I think she really
is just trying to help.

03:55.694 --> 03:57.779
She's introducing me
to her dad this weekend.

03:59.156 --> 04:02.117
‐ You are meeting with a damn music mogul.

04:02.117 --> 04:04.203
I mean, he's been in
hot tubs with Rihanna,

04:04.203 --> 04:06.413
he's been thanked in more
Grammy speeches than God.

04:06.413 --> 04:08.957
‐ I mean, minus the country
music categories, but...

04:08.957 --> 04:11.585
I'm super nervous.
I mean, if he likes me,

04:11.585 --> 04:15.130
I think this could lead to me
working for a freaking record label.

04:15.130 --> 04:18.842
‐ Well, I'm also meeting a very
important dad this weekend, too.

04:18.842 --> 04:19.843
Bruno's.

04:21.011 --> 04:24.640
‐ Uh, I might be in love with
your girlfriend's baby daddy.

04:24.640 --> 04:26.767
‐ Well, I wouldn't mind. But,
his boyfriend, on the other hand...

04:27.893 --> 04:29.603
‐ Am I the only straight person
left in Los Angeles?

04:29.603 --> 04:32.272
‐ Yes. Liv and Lucas met in college,

04:32.272 --> 04:34.525
and Bruno was conceived in a...

04:34.525 --> 04:36.360
"maybe we're bi" moment.

04:36.360 --> 04:39.071
‐ Hm. Maybe I need a moment like that.

04:39.071 --> 04:41.448
‐ No. You are deeply straight.

04:41.448 --> 04:43.450
And I don't mean that as a compliment.

04:46.203 --> 04:48.080
‐ [gasps] Ooh!

04:48.080 --> 04:51.458
This means three more pee stops,
but thank you.

04:51.458 --> 04:53.293
‐ Thanks for giving me a ride.
‐ Oh,

04:53.293 --> 04:54.962
it's literally on the way
to my parents' house.

04:54.962 --> 04:58.298
[shuts door]
So, what is this place again?

04:58.298 --> 05:01.927
‐ Oh, it's like a spa vineyard situation.

05:01.927 --> 05:04.721
You know, it'll kinda be
my post‐breakup "eat, pray, love."

05:04.721 --> 05:07.099
Although, realistically for me,
more of a...

05:07.099 --> 05:10.018
"sip, soak, cry."

05:10.018 --> 05:11.687
Are you excited to see your parents?

05:11.687 --> 05:13.272
‐ Yeah.

05:13.272 --> 05:16.400
It's a little sad to say goodbye
to my childhood home.

05:16.400 --> 05:18.694
All my best psychological
damage happened there.

05:18.694 --> 05:21.947
‐ Same. My childhood home
was basically like a trauma center.

05:21.947 --> 05:24.116
♪

05:24.116 --> 05:26.243
‐ Wow. It's happening.

05:26.243 --> 05:29.204
My people are talking, having a...

05:29.204 --> 05:31.999
water together.

05:31.999 --> 05:35.252
‐ I mean, I guess we can't have alcohol
before going to a kid thing, right?

05:35.252 --> 05:37.462
‐ Uh, you haven't met
some of the straight parents.

05:37.462 --> 05:39.965
Lives of very loud desperation.

05:39.965 --> 05:41.466
LIV:
Yeah.

05:42.176 --> 05:43.802
I'm gonna go change.

05:45.804 --> 05:47.806
I went too hard on the mom look, right?

05:47.806 --> 05:49.266
‐ Yeah.
‐ Please.

05:49.266 --> 05:50.976
‐ Cool.

05:52.311 --> 05:54.062
[sighs]

05:54.062 --> 05:57.441
‐ Um, Bruno is the coolest kid ever.

05:57.441 --> 06:00.652
Yeah, no, seriously.
Kudos to your DNA. [laughs]

06:00.652 --> 06:02.863
‐ We're really lucky. [laughs]

06:02.863 --> 06:05.449
You and Liv, you must be getting really,

06:05.449 --> 06:07.075
really serious.

06:07.075 --> 06:09.411
She's never introduced
Bruno to anyone before.

06:11.371 --> 06:12.873
Ever.

06:12.873 --> 06:15.334
♪

06:15.334 --> 06:17.794
‐ I'm really nervous.
‐ Why are you nervous?

06:17.794 --> 06:20.506
It's your dad.
‐ He can be really...

06:20.506 --> 06:22.799
Well, you know how moguls are.
[laughs]

06:22.799 --> 06:24.968
He's just hard on me
because he was self‐made,

06:24.968 --> 06:27.346
and it's my fault that he was
rich when I was born?

06:27.346 --> 06:29.389
‐ [laughs]
Well, very smart move by baby you.

06:29.389 --> 06:31.475
‐ [laughs] No, he's gonna love you.

06:31.475 --> 06:33.185
He's been judgmental
of my friends in the past

06:33.185 --> 06:35.646
just because they're always in rehab
or Spain or whatever,

06:35.646 --> 06:38.440
but you're the real deal.

06:38.440 --> 06:39.691
And it's gonna prove to my dad

06:39.691 --> 06:42.861
that I've been taking my Hillslope job
seriously. I've got my shit together.

06:43.445 --> 06:45.447
‐ Cool, so no pressure. [laughs]

06:46.949 --> 06:49.910
DJ [on radio]: Good afternoon,
Palo Alto. This is Ricky Riley.

06:49.910 --> 06:52.037
Let's get ready for the weekend.

06:52.037 --> 06:55.541
You're listening to HOT 87.6,
playing all the hits from the '80s, '90s,

06:55.541 --> 06:58.669
and, well, yeah. Just from then.
‐ Wow, Jesus.

06:58.669 --> 07:02.381
Ricky Riley's been the DJ at this station
since people used fax machines.

07:02.381 --> 07:05.759
RICKY: We're giving out free Sugar Ray
tickets to our first three callers.

07:07.427 --> 07:10.472
‐ My god, my mom would always make us
call into this station, like, 1,000 times,

07:10.472 --> 07:13.433
trying to win free tickets. We never won.

07:13.433 --> 07:15.811
She said, uh, the only thing
she ever won was me.

07:15.811 --> 07:18.313
‐ Aw. Well, you're her baby girl.

07:18.313 --> 07:20.107
‐ Yeah.

07:20.107 --> 07:22.651
When you grow up with someone
who tells you you walk on water,

07:22.651 --> 07:26.071
then you get out into
the real world, and, uh, you sink...

07:26.071 --> 07:28.991
‐ I was told I was gonna sink,
and then I did.

07:28.991 --> 07:31.618
I do feel like mine's similar, but worse.

07:31.618 --> 07:33.412
‐ There was this one concert,

07:33.412 --> 07:37.040
uh, the headliner was the Sorcerer,
who I was totally obsessed with.

07:37.040 --> 07:39.293
‐ Oh my god, the guy with the long hair?

07:39.293 --> 07:40.794
‐ I was pretty much in love with him.

07:40.794 --> 07:43.505
My mom really, really wanted me
to win that one, but...

07:44.798 --> 07:46.842
I wouldn't even let her call.

07:46.842 --> 07:49.303
I just lied and said I didn't wanna go.

07:50.053 --> 07:51.638
‐ What? Why?

07:53.140 --> 07:56.602
‐ 'Cause I thought there was zero chance
of winning, so I didn't wanna play.

07:58.353 --> 08:00.939
‐ Okay, maybe your trauma
is worse than mine.

08:01.857 --> 08:03.692
‐ Thank you.

08:03.692 --> 08:05.152
Ooh, we're almost at your wine spa.

08:07.279 --> 08:10.282
♪

08:19.291 --> 08:22.294
♪ angelic music ♪

08:23.128 --> 08:26.256
‐ Wow. This place is... [laughs]

08:28.258 --> 08:29.760
Can I have my ashes spread here?

08:29.760 --> 08:32.012
[laughs] Not today, but, um...

08:33.222 --> 08:35.224
Uh, the reservation is under...

08:37.184 --> 08:38.602
Alison.

08:39.144 --> 08:40.521
ALISON J:
Cutie pie!

08:41.813 --> 08:43.315
Ah!

08:44.441 --> 08:46.151
Yay, yay, yay!

08:46.151 --> 08:48.278
♪ foreboding music ♪

08:48.278 --> 08:49.780
My god, how are you?
[laughs]

08:52.824 --> 08:55.827
♪

08:56.787 --> 08:58.539
[Craig laughing]
‐ She's here!

08:58.539 --> 09:00.791
[laughing]
‐ Dad,

09:00.791 --> 09:03.669
it's not 1996. Why are you
filming me with a camcorder?

09:03.669 --> 09:05.754
‐ I found it packing up the basement.

09:05.754 --> 09:08.966
Your mother said it wouldn't still work,
but I futzed with it.

09:08.966 --> 09:11.718
‐ Yeah, it wasn't meant
to be a challenge, Craig.

09:11.718 --> 09:14.847
Honey, go outside to the car
and get Jules' bag.

09:14.847 --> 09:16.682
CRAIG: You talking to me?

09:16.682 --> 09:19.309
‐ It's gonna be quite the experience
when you and dad live in an apartment,

09:19.309 --> 09:21.520
and you'll always be able
to hear each other, huh?

09:21.520 --> 09:23.522
‐ [laughs] You're funny.

09:24.439 --> 09:27.317
‐ [sighs] Nothing like
coming home to be confronted

09:27.317 --> 09:29.736
with your future in memoriam slide show.

09:29.736 --> 09:32.823
‐ Yeah, I told your father
to pack those at the end,

09:32.823 --> 09:35.993
so that we could look at you
to the last possible minute.

09:35.993 --> 09:38.245
‐ [sighs] You look great, Mom.

09:38.245 --> 09:41.540
‐ Ugh, I look terrible. You look great.

09:41.540 --> 09:43.292
You are gorgeous.

09:43.292 --> 09:46.253
‐ Wait, are you throwing out
all of your pottery?

09:47.421 --> 09:49.965
‐ Who would want anything I made?

09:49.965 --> 09:52.342
Who I do wanna talk about is you,

09:52.342 --> 09:55.304
my beautiful grown girl,

09:55.304 --> 09:57.598
living that fabulous LA life.

09:57.598 --> 10:00.142
‐ Oh god, it's not that fabulous, Mom.
‐ Come on.

10:00.142 --> 10:02.436
Your big promotion? I just saw your, um,

10:02.436 --> 10:04.396
I saw your boss on Kelly Ripa.

10:04.396 --> 10:06.565
Not a pore between the two of them.

10:06.565 --> 10:09.067
‐ Yeah, Celeste is pretty pretty.

10:10.068 --> 10:13.322
But, I'm, uh, I'm not sure Woöm
is the best for me anymore, actually.

10:14.072 --> 10:15.490
‐ Something's wrong.

10:16.200 --> 10:17.409
What's wrong?

10:18.035 --> 10:20.454
Uh, it's actually not about work.

10:20.454 --> 10:22.497
Madison and I are in a...

10:22.497 --> 10:24.374
in a weird thing. She's...

10:24.374 --> 10:25.876
been hanging out
with this other girl a lot.

10:25.876 --> 10:26.877
‐ [scoffs] Come on!

10:26.877 --> 10:29.713
What does this other girl
have that you don't have?

10:29.713 --> 10:32.424
‐ Mm, uh, let's see.
A literal billion dollars?

10:33.842 --> 10:36.178
‐ Trust me. Madison knows

10:36.178 --> 10:39.765
that there is not a friend in
the world that's better than you.

10:39.765 --> 10:42.184
No contest. Just break the ice,

10:42.184 --> 10:45.187
text her. She'll be
so happy to hear from you.

10:45.687 --> 10:47.189
‐ Alright, fine.

10:50.984 --> 10:53.987
[typing]

10:53.987 --> 10:55.239
[sends text]

10:55.239 --> 10:58.367
[laughs]
[restaurant chatter]

11:02.955 --> 11:03.997
‐ Oh, he's coming.

11:03.997 --> 11:05.958
Put your phone away.
He always gives me shit about that.

11:07.793 --> 11:09.419
ANDRE:
Sorry I'm late.

11:09.419 --> 11:11.338
Ed Sheeran is driving me insane.

11:11.338 --> 11:14.883
‐ [laughs] Uh, Dad,
this is my friend Madison Maxwell,

11:14.883 --> 11:17.261
publicist extraordinaire.

11:17.261 --> 11:18.679
‐ It is such an honor to meet you.

11:20.097 --> 11:21.390
‐ Okay, I'm not the Dalai Lama.

11:22.516 --> 11:24.017
Close. [laughs]

11:24.935 --> 11:27.020
Oh shit, Pink is here.

11:27.020 --> 11:28.730
Let me go kiss her ass for one minute.

11:32.192 --> 11:34.194
‐ You can sit down now.
‐ Oh.

11:34.194 --> 11:36.655
♪

11:36.655 --> 11:38.615
‐ So, I've already gotten you started

11:38.615 --> 11:41.577
at sorting your things out,
kind of separating...

11:41.577 --> 11:43.287
Oh, this I almost forgot.

11:43.287 --> 11:44.830
‐ Oh god, Mom, with all due respect,

11:44.830 --> 11:47.749
I don't think my baby teeth need
to make the move to your condo.

11:47.749 --> 11:50.627
[phone buzzing]

11:55.340 --> 11:56.592
‐ What's wrong now?

11:56.592 --> 11:58.594
‐ Nothing. Nothing. Um...

11:59.636 --> 12:02.139
You know what? I'm just gonna throw
all this out. Do you have trash bags‐‐

12:02.139 --> 12:03.599
‐ Oh no, no, no! No, y‐‐

12:03.599 --> 12:05.642
You can't toss this out. This is special.

12:05.642 --> 12:08.145
‐ Why? You're throwing out
all the pottery you made.

12:08.145 --> 12:10.397
‐ [scoffs] That's just me. It's...

12:10.397 --> 12:11.607
That's different.

12:11.607 --> 12:13.483
‐ Mom, it's not different.
This isn't special.

12:13.483 --> 12:14.985
This is garbage!
[rattling]

12:15.652 --> 12:17.779
‐ [scoffs] You... Whoa...

12:17.779 --> 12:19.781
That's real nice.

12:20.741 --> 12:22.451
‐ [sighs] God...

12:25.287 --> 12:26.622
ALISON J:
Well,

12:26.622 --> 12:28.290
let me just say on behalf

12:28.290 --> 12:30.417
of both the Alisons and myself,

12:30.417 --> 12:34.087
we are thrilled you're considering
our offer. It's thrilling.

12:34.963 --> 12:38.175
‐ Well, I would say I'm, um,
considering considering it.

12:38.175 --> 12:40.260
[laughs] It's not yet fully considered,

12:40.260 --> 12:42.763
but, uh, thank you
for saying the word thrilling.

12:43.805 --> 12:46.308
‐ Well, we are very serious
about you joining our team, Izzy.

12:46.308 --> 12:49.144
That is why we are wining
and whining you.

12:49.144 --> 12:52.523
‐ Um, that's thrilling. [nervous laugh]

12:52.523 --> 12:56.235
But, um, I just‐‐ I don't know
if I'm quite ready to leave Woöm

12:56.235 --> 12:58.028
just yet.
‐ Yeah.

12:58.028 --> 13:00.948
I mean, do you think Celeste
would ever give you a weekend like this?

13:01.490 --> 13:03.200
‐ Uh...
ALISON: Well,

13:03.200 --> 13:04.910
we are expanding into a rosé brand.

13:05.410 --> 13:08.747
And as head of branded,
I'm spearheading the entire process.

13:08.747 --> 13:11.500
Yeah. Alison B was actually
supposed to be here with me,

13:11.500 --> 13:14.461
but, sleepy little angel, she wanted you

13:14.461 --> 13:16.338
to have her entire comped deluxe suite.

13:16.338 --> 13:19.341
‐ Wow. Yeah, that's so generous.

13:19.341 --> 13:22.261
It's crazy you can order
a massage through the TV.

13:23.011 --> 13:24.388
‐ So cute.

13:24.388 --> 13:26.807
Uh, so which one of
these is your favorite?

13:26.807 --> 13:28.892
‐ Oh. Uh,

13:28.892 --> 13:30.143
I would say that one.

13:30.143 --> 13:32.896
It wasn't too sweet,
but it was still fruity.

13:32.896 --> 13:34.940
The other ones felt
a little bit like I was drinking,

13:34.940 --> 13:36.567
like, an expensive Starburst.

13:36.567 --> 13:39.444
‐ Okay, great.
That decides it. This is the one.

13:39.444 --> 13:41.029
‐ Yeah, excuse me!

13:41.029 --> 13:43.782
This is our new signature rosé.

13:43.782 --> 13:45.576
‐ What?
‐ Yes!

13:45.576 --> 13:46.952
Congrats.

13:46.952 --> 13:49.329
[nervous laugh]

13:49.329 --> 13:51.957
[kids shrieking, screaming]

13:51.957 --> 13:53.959
♪

13:53.959 --> 13:55.210
COUNSELOR:
Okay, families!

13:55.210 --> 13:58.130
Let's have you guys huddle up for
the color war. We'll get you set up.

13:58.881 --> 14:02.217
Here we go, champ!
One for your mom, one for your dad.

14:02.217 --> 14:04.636
‐ But, I want Stella to have a shirt, too.

14:04.636 --> 14:06.471
She's part of our team.
‐ Oh,

14:06.471 --> 14:08.557
I‐I really don't need one, bud.

14:08.557 --> 14:10.100
I promise you, I'm good.

14:10.100 --> 14:12.186
‐ I‐I'm sorry,
you must be Bruno's stepmom?

14:12.186 --> 14:14.438
‐ Oh, no. I'm, uh, just a girlfriend.

14:16.356 --> 14:17.733
‐ Her girlfriend.

14:18.525 --> 14:19.526
‐ What's up?

14:20.027 --> 14:21.403
‐ Oh.

14:21.403 --> 14:23.614
Can I get another red shirt over here?

14:23.614 --> 14:25.115
It's another throuple.

14:27.576 --> 14:30.078
‐ So, Marilyn, tell me about yourself.

14:30.078 --> 14:32.372
‐ Uh, well, uh, I've been doing PR

14:32.372 --> 14:35.209
for the last five years, and‐‐
‐ You know,

14:35.209 --> 14:37.294
the last girl Ruby tried
to get me to hire on tour

14:38.170 --> 14:40.506
got us permanently banned
from The Peninsula in Hong Kong.

14:41.340 --> 14:43.008
‐ [nervous laugh] That was, uh,

14:43.008 --> 14:44.927
mostly a misunderstanding, Dad.

14:44.927 --> 14:47.054
‐ Was it also a misunderstanding

14:47.054 --> 14:50.265
when your coke dealer friend
stole Tyler the Creator's Grammy

14:50.265 --> 14:51.350
at our holiday party?

14:51.350 --> 14:54.019
‐ That was a joke.
She was gonna give it back.

14:54.019 --> 14:56.313
Tyler thought it was funny.

14:56.313 --> 14:58.565
‐ Tyler's not rude. Back to you.

14:58.565 --> 15:01.193
♪ music playing ♪

15:01.193 --> 15:03.946
You a druggie?
‐ Nope!

15:03.946 --> 15:06.573
But, I do have an addictive personality.

15:06.573 --> 15:08.283
But, it's mostly channeled

15:08.283 --> 15:10.369
into coffee, Soul Cycle, and work.
ANDRE: Hm.

15:10.369 --> 15:12.538
You think you can teach
my daughter how to get into that?

15:12.538 --> 15:14.623
‐ Dad, I've been working
really hard at the label.

15:14.623 --> 15:16.458
I'm in the office every day.

15:16.458 --> 15:18.168
‐ Hard? [laughs]

15:18.168 --> 15:19.920
My assistant said that you expensed

15:19.920 --> 15:22.339
a $4,000 desk chair.

15:22.339 --> 15:24.174
Glad it's getting some use.

15:24.174 --> 15:25.634
‐ Anyway, this is about Madison.

15:25.634 --> 15:27.678
ANDRE:
Who?

15:27.678 --> 15:29.763
‐ That'd be me.
‐ Oh, yeah.

15:29.763 --> 15:30.931
Sure, she seems great.

15:30.931 --> 15:33.433
‐ Yep, I'm just, honestly,
so excited for the opportunity

15:33.433 --> 15:35.644
to get more involved with the label,
and for the tour‐‐

15:35.644 --> 15:37.521
‐ You know, I'm not gonna
let you trash my jet again.

15:38.564 --> 15:41.066
You're gonna fly commercial to Australia.

15:41.066 --> 15:44.194
[ringtone playing]

15:44.194 --> 15:46.697
[typing, sends text]
Look, I gotta get back to work.

15:47.739 --> 15:49.658
I'm impressed by your drive, Madison.

15:50.784 --> 15:52.911
Maybe you'll rub off on her in Australia.

15:55.622 --> 15:57.958
‐ Uh, thank you.
It was so nice meeting you.

15:57.958 --> 16:00.169
‐ [laughs] I know.

16:03.922 --> 16:06.925
♪

16:07.509 --> 16:10.262
‐ The truth is we do make a hot throuple.

16:10.262 --> 16:13.265
‐ Really? I feel like
we look like the Wiggles.

16:13.265 --> 16:16.894
‐ The... I'm not sure what the Wiggles
are, but they don't sound very hot.

16:16.894 --> 16:19.271
‐ Lucas, do you not
watch kids' stuff with him?

16:19.271 --> 16:21.523
‐ Uh, no, but we‐we did

16:21.523 --> 16:23.817
just binge watch Mare of Easttown.
‐ Oh. Love.

16:24.610 --> 16:26.153
‐ Oh...
‐ Oh!

16:26.153 --> 16:28.655
[nervous laugh]
That is not a good Liv look.

16:28.655 --> 16:30.407
‐ Yeah, Mario said that
she was gonna kill me.

16:30.407 --> 16:31.909
‐ Who's Mario?

16:31.909 --> 16:33.577
‐ Oh, uh, he's my boyfriend.

16:33.577 --> 16:37.122
‐ Oh, no way! Wow.
Why didn't you bring him here?

16:38.540 --> 16:40.417
‐ Uh, Lucas doesn't

16:40.417 --> 16:42.669
feel ready to have Mario meet Bruno.

16:45.339 --> 16:47.925
‐ Oh. Hm.
BRUNO: Look.

16:47.925 --> 16:49.843
♪

16:50.511 --> 16:51.762
‐ Aw.
‐ Wow.

16:53.514 --> 16:54.848
Oh...

16:56.058 --> 16:57.559
[nervous whimper]

17:02.606 --> 17:05.609
[phone buzzing]

17:07.444 --> 17:10.364
‐ Hey. Look who it is.
I thought you were on the road again.

17:10.364 --> 17:12.699
‐ I am. We're just packing up from a show.

17:12.699 --> 17:14.826
I have something really
important I need to tell you.

17:15.953 --> 17:16.954
‐ Okay.

17:17.538 --> 17:20.040
‐ I saw the world's
largest ball of twine, Jules.

17:21.124 --> 17:24.711
And, uh, that just felt like
something you needed to know.

17:25.838 --> 17:29.132
‐ I mean, it was,
and I feel incredibly seen right now.

17:29.132 --> 17:31.218
How's the tour?
FENDER [on phone]: It's good.

17:31.218 --> 17:32.970
We went through Kansas yesterday.

17:32.970 --> 17:35.138
You know, as someone
who's not from this country,

17:35.138 --> 17:38.141
I am really leaning into
the whole Americana thing.

17:38.725 --> 17:40.936
Like, I'm wearing a cowboy hat right now.

17:40.936 --> 17:42.646
‐ Oh, I'm holding my own baby teeth.

17:43.313 --> 17:46.358
‐ Uh, way to bury the lead.
JULES [on phone]: I, uh,

17:46.358 --> 17:49.653
had to come home to my parents'
house and help them pack up.

17:49.653 --> 17:51.655
It's very... a lot.

17:52.489 --> 17:54.908
I‐I'm sure Kansas is more fun though.

17:55.534 --> 17:56.994
‐ Cowboy, take me away.

17:56.994 --> 17:58.495
‐ Ooh, a Chicks fan.

18:00.372 --> 18:02.583
Hey, what about the Sorcerer?
Do you remember him?

18:02.583 --> 18:05.460
FENDER:
Uh, of course. His shows are legendary.

18:05.460 --> 18:07.671
‐ Yeah. I never made it to one.

18:07.671 --> 18:11.300
‐ Uh, I think we're done packing up,
so I gotta get back on the bus, but, um,

18:12.384 --> 18:14.178
I'm really glad I got to say hi.

18:14.761 --> 18:16.930
‐ Yeah, me, too.
FENDER: See you, Jules.

18:18.849 --> 18:19.975
[hangs up]

18:21.393 --> 18:22.895
[sighs]

18:24.188 --> 18:25.689
‐ You're still hot.

18:27.524 --> 18:31.028
♪ foreboding music ♪

18:31.028 --> 18:34.031
[crows cawing]

18:36.783 --> 18:38.785
Where in the literal hell...

18:46.502 --> 18:48.921
RICKY [echoing]:
Welcome to HOT 87.6,

18:48.921 --> 18:51.089
Jules' own personal hell.

18:51.089 --> 18:52.716
We're playing all of the top hits

18:52.716 --> 18:54.718
from her unspecial life.

18:54.718 --> 18:57.721
♪

18:57.721 --> 19:00.724
[rummaging]

19:03.185 --> 19:04.770
JULES:
Mom?

19:04.770 --> 19:08.106
‐ You were right.
We gotta get rid of this stuff.

19:08.106 --> 19:10.234
‐ Hey! My mom made that!
CAT LADY: Oh,

19:10.234 --> 19:12.402
this we can keep.

19:12.402 --> 19:14.446
"Most unspecial."

19:14.446 --> 19:16.323
[Jules sighs]
Here! Take it!

19:17.115 --> 19:18.158
‐ Very funny.

19:18.158 --> 19:20.786
‐ That's what you think
of yourself, isn't it?

19:20.786 --> 19:22.371
You can't win!

19:22.371 --> 19:25.207
You don't wanna meet the big rock star.

19:25.207 --> 19:27.626
‐ Meet him? Is he here?
‐ We're in

19:27.626 --> 19:30.587
this freaking hellscape! Look around!

19:31.296 --> 19:33.757
‐ Are we in the poster?
‐ What do you care?

19:33.757 --> 19:36.051
You didn't even wanna go to his concert.

19:36.051 --> 19:37.970
‐ I did! [sighs]

19:37.970 --> 19:40.639
I shouldn't have said
that I didn't. I shouldn't...

19:40.639 --> 19:42.599
I shouldn't be so scared.

19:43.267 --> 19:45.310
‐ Of what?

19:45.310 --> 19:48.605
‐ That I'm not special or whatever.

19:48.605 --> 19:51.608
♪

19:53.402 --> 19:55.279
I am.

19:55.279 --> 19:57.322
‐ Yeah.

19:57.322 --> 19:59.116
You are.

20:01.451 --> 20:03.704
[crow cawing]

20:04.288 --> 20:05.789
‐ It's you.

20:16.300 --> 20:17.801
[gasps]

20:28.896 --> 20:31.023
[Ruby sighs]

20:31.023 --> 20:32.941
‐ My dad is such a dick.

20:32.941 --> 20:34.526
‐ I'm so sorry, Ruby.

20:34.526 --> 20:37.446
‐ No matter what I do,
he just sees me as a spoiled brat.

20:37.446 --> 20:41.283
I mean, I've been busting my ass
at Hillslope for, like, four months now.

20:41.283 --> 20:43.202
‐ Yeah.

20:43.202 --> 20:45.787
Wait. Wait, you've only been
there for four months?

20:45.787 --> 20:46.872
What were you doing before?

20:47.497 --> 20:49.291
‐ What are you? On his side?

20:49.291 --> 20:50.918
♪ piano music ♪

20:50.918 --> 20:52.544
You know what? Fuck my dad.

20:52.544 --> 20:55.589
And fuck the label,
and fuck Australia. I'm quitting.

20:55.589 --> 20:57.591
‐ Wait, you're not gonna
come with us on the tour?

20:58.509 --> 21:00.052
‐ Come with you?

21:00.052 --> 21:01.553
You're my friend.

21:01.553 --> 21:03.055
If I'm not going, you're not going.

21:03.889 --> 21:06.183
‐ Look, of course I'm your friend,

21:06.183 --> 21:08.143
but this is also my career.

21:08.143 --> 21:10.938
You know this is a big opportunity for me.
[Ruby scoffs]

21:11.438 --> 21:13.857
‐ Wow! So, there it is.

21:13.857 --> 21:16.610
‐ What?
‐ I thought you were different.

21:16.610 --> 21:18.779
But, you've just been
using me like every other

21:18.779 --> 21:20.822
desperate girl who wants to be my friend.

21:20.822 --> 21:22.741
‐ I'm sorry, desperate?

21:22.741 --> 21:26.161
You're the one buying elaborate gifts
and inviting me everywhere.

21:26.161 --> 21:29.164
Look, you insisted on
helping me because you wanted to.

21:29.164 --> 21:31.750
‐ You should've seen yourself
with my dad just now.

21:31.750 --> 21:35.504
Sucking up to him?
You were basically flirting.

21:35.504 --> 21:38.757
But I guess I shouldn't be surprised.
Rich older guys are your type.

21:39.716 --> 21:42.511
‐ Are you fucking serious right now?

21:42.511 --> 21:45.472
I was trying to impress him
because you literally told me to.

21:45.472 --> 21:48.600
‐ Well, I'm literally telling you
to go home and forget about the tour

21:49.518 --> 21:51.395
because it's not happening
for either of us.

21:59.653 --> 22:01.405
‐ Jules never liked you.

22:07.119 --> 22:10.122
[kids screaming]

22:12.040 --> 22:14.418
‐ Hey. You okay?

22:14.418 --> 22:15.794
‐ Hey.

22:15.794 --> 22:17.087
Yeah. [clears throat]

22:18.213 --> 22:19.214
No.

22:20.382 --> 22:22.176
‐ Is Lucas being weird?

22:22.843 --> 22:25.846
‐ I mean, a little, but it's not Lucas.

22:25.846 --> 22:26.847
He's a good dad.

22:28.056 --> 22:30.475
‐ Okay, well, is it me?
‐ No.

22:35.105 --> 22:36.607
It's my mom.

22:37.357 --> 22:38.650
‐ Your mom?

22:42.905 --> 22:45.032
‐ Before my mom met my stepdad,

22:45.032 --> 22:48.035
she was a revolving door of boyfriends.

22:48.035 --> 22:49.536
You know, and it sucked.

22:50.662 --> 22:52.623
I don't wanna be like those guys that

22:52.623 --> 22:55.209
came into my life, showed up
to three of my volleyball games,

22:55.209 --> 22:56.627
and then bailed. You know,

22:56.627 --> 22:58.962
I‐I don't wanna do that to Bruno.

23:00.130 --> 23:03.133
‐ Why are you saying that
like you're going somewhere?

23:04.635 --> 23:06.303
‐ I don't know, I mean, you know,

23:06.303 --> 23:08.597
what if I decide to go back to school?

23:09.515 --> 23:10.807
‐ You might go back to school?

23:11.642 --> 23:14.811
‐ We don't know if the bar is
gonna be a success or not, so‐‐

23:14.811 --> 23:16.522
‐ Wha‐‐ No, I do! It is!

23:16.522 --> 23:18.565
Why haven't you talked to me
about this before, Stella?

23:18.565 --> 23:21.235
‐ Because I am not used to
having to talk to anyone else

23:21.235 --> 23:23.237
when I make big life decisions, okay?

23:23.237 --> 23:25.113
I just do it.

23:25.113 --> 23:27.241
I've never had to consider anyone else,

23:27.241 --> 23:29.618
but now, I have two people
I have to think about.

23:29.618 --> 23:32.079
And one of them is really tiny

23:32.079 --> 23:33.580
and adorable.

23:35.332 --> 23:37.960
‐ Okay, so... what are you saying?

23:40.337 --> 23:41.421
[sighs]

23:43.340 --> 23:44.842
‐ I don't know...

23:51.849 --> 23:53.350
[inhales]

23:54.268 --> 23:55.894
[exhales]

24:00.482 --> 24:02.901
‐ Hi.
‐ Oh, hey.

24:05.821 --> 24:08.699
‐ I'm sorry for being weird
about the teeth in the trash.

24:09.283 --> 24:11.285
You should keep everything
that's important to you.

24:13.495 --> 24:15.080
Speaking of, um...

24:15.831 --> 24:18.292
do you think I could have this vase?

24:18.292 --> 24:21.086
I have a place in my house
I'd really to put it.

24:21.086 --> 24:23.422
‐ Of course. I mean,

24:23.422 --> 24:26.258
it is an ashtray, but yes,
I'd love for you to have it. [laughs]

24:26.258 --> 24:27.759
‐ Thanks, Mom.

24:29.136 --> 24:31.680
Mom, you know I think you're amazing.
‐ Well,

24:31.680 --> 24:34.683
uh, thank you.
I think I'm amazing, too. [laughs]

24:36.435 --> 24:38.520
I know I'm special.

24:38.520 --> 24:40.022
I'm special

24:40.022 --> 24:42.649
because I get to be your mom. [laughs]

24:42.649 --> 24:45.485
♪

24:45.485 --> 24:46.486
[laughs]

24:47.946 --> 24:49.198
Thank you.

24:52.201 --> 24:54.703
‐ Dad! What are you doing? Really?

24:58.040 --> 24:59.833
‐ [laughs] Well, uh,
thanks for this weekend.

24:59.833 --> 25:01.710
It's given me
a weird day hangover,

25:01.710 --> 25:03.378
but a lot to think about.

25:03.378 --> 25:05.714
‐ Ooh! Enough to make a decision?

25:05.714 --> 25:07.716
‐ I'm not sure.

25:07.716 --> 25:08.842
♪

25:08.842 --> 25:12.679
Um, my relationship
with Celeste is complicated.

25:12.679 --> 25:16.141
I know she won't notice me
the way I want her to, but...

25:17.017 --> 25:19.770
I guess I really do look up to her.

25:19.770 --> 25:21.647
‐ Listen, Izzy,

25:21.647 --> 25:24.483
we didn't wanna have to tell you this,
but there's something you should know.

25:26.527 --> 25:28.779
You're being loyal to Celeste,

25:28.779 --> 25:30.781
but she's not being loyal to you.

25:30.781 --> 25:33.784
♪

25:38.330 --> 25:41.291
‐ I'll be there in 30 minutes.
Are you a brand new Izzy?

25:41.750 --> 25:45.587
‐ Um, actually,
I'm gonna stay one more night. Um...

25:46.255 --> 25:49.550
I'll just fly out tomorrow morning.
Th‐they gave me an extra night for free

25:49.550 --> 25:52.678
because, uh, my skin‐contact wine
had no skin contact.

25:52.678 --> 25:55.013
‐ Please stop saying skin‐contact.

25:55.013 --> 25:58.183
Okay, well, I'll see you tomorrow.
Don't forget it's Monday staff meeting.

25:58.183 --> 26:01.186
‐ Totally. Uh, okay. Uh, drive safe.

26:03.814 --> 26:05.858
‐ Hello. [laughs]

26:05.858 --> 26:08.277
No, no, no, this way, cutie. [laughs]

